              <h3>Worked examples</h3>
              <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-4 mb-2">
                Example 1 – Convert 3.2 tonnes to kilograms
              </h4>
              <ol>
                <li>Write down the formula: <code>kg = t × 1,000</code>.</li>
                <li>Substitute the value: <code>kg = 3.2 × 1,000</code>.</li>
                <li>Calculate: <code>kg = 3,200</code>.</li>
              </ol>
              <p><strong>Answer:</strong> 3.2 t = 3,200 kg.</p>

              <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold mt-4 mb-2">
                Example 2 – Convert 18,750 kg to tonnes
              </h4>
              <ol>
                <li>Use the inverse formula: <code>t = kg ÷ 1,000</code>.</li>
                <li>Substitute the value: <code>t = 18,750 ÷ 1,000</code>.</li>
                <li>Calculate: <code>t = 18.75</code>.</li>
              </ol>
              <p><strong>Answer:</strong> 18,750 kg = 18.75 t.</p>

              <h2>Tonnes vs tons: what’s the difference?</h2>
              <p>
                The words <strong>tonne</strong> and <strong>ton</strong> are
                often confused, but they are not the same:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Tonne (metric ton)</strong>: exactly
                  <strong>1,000 kg</strong>. Used in most of the world and in
                  the SI system.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>US short ton</strong>: <strong>2,000 lb</strong> ≈
                  <strong>907.185 kg</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>UK long ton</strong>: <strong>2,240 lb</strong> ≈
                  <strong>1,016.047 kg</strong>.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This calculator uses the <strong>metric tonne (t)</strong> only.
                If your data is in US or UK tons, convert to kilograms first
                using the appropriate factor, then you can convert to tonnes if
                needed.
              </p>

              <h2>When are tonnes and kilograms used?</h2>
              <p>Tonnes and kilograms are both metric units of mass:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Kilograms (kg)</strong> are used for everyday weights:
                  people, luggage, small packages, etc.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Tonnes (t)</strong> are used for large quantities:
                  cargo shipments, vehicles, industrial materials, agricultural
                  yields, and CO₂ emissions.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Because 1 tonne = 1,000 kg, using tonnes keeps large numbers
                more readable. For example, instead of writing 125,000 kg you
                can write 125 t.
              </p>

              <h2>FAQ: tonnes to kilograms</h2>
              <h3>How many kilograms are in a tonne?</h3>
              <p>
                Exactly <strong>1,000 kilograms</strong>. The tonne is defined
                that way in the metric system.
              </p>

              <h3>How do I quickly convert in my head?</h3>
              <p>
                To go from tonnes to kilograms, just
                <strong>add three zeros</strong> (multiply by 1,000). To go from
                kilograms to tonnes,
                <strong>move the decimal point three places to the left</strong
                >.
              </p>

              <h3>Does this calculator support decimals?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. You can enter decimal values like <code>0.75</code> t or
                <code>1234.56</code> kg. Use the “Decimal places” selector to
                control how many digits are shown in the result.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I convert a whole list of values?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Use the <strong>batch converter</strong> above: paste your
                tonne values (from Excel, CSV, etc.) and click “Convert list” to
                get the kilogram values line by line.
              </p>
